data:
The Project "Majorana on the M.O.V.E.” (Mobilities as Opportunities to Value European inclusive culture), planned by I.I.S.S. “Ettore Majorana” in Seriate (BG), aims at supporting in service training of  the staff, combining two kinds of mobility experiences: structured courses on language and methodology, and job shadowing and school visit activities in schools in several European countries. 
As for job shadowing and school visit activities, we’ll be working with schools and colleges which, in different socio-economic and geographic realities (United Kingdom, Finland, and Malta), have already dealt with the educational and cultural problems presented by the presence of migrants, and so have already developed new methodologies to be used for students with special needs of any kind. As for structured courses, we have chosen courses of English language and methodology (with special reference to CLIL and teaching immigrants and students with special needs of any kind), offered by schools of English in the UK with long experience and a certified level of quality.  
Activities have been carefully selected by an appointed Project team in order to meet the organisation's needs in terms of quality development in teaching and learning, modernisation and internationalisation. 
The general objective of the project is focused on improving teachers’ linguistic and methodological competencies, but also on enhancing interactions among all the people who work in our school and who are required to establish good relationships with families and with a reality which is becoming more and more complex.
More specifically, the project aims at:
• improving language skills and culture competences for the staff and, as a consequence, for the students, who will be equipped with advanced language skills to be used in the various job sectors which characterize our region and will be able to tackle the needs of a global and interconnected economy;
• promoting the practical classroom skills of the teachers, thus making the class more inclusive towards any kind of diversity, with special reference to the cultural diversities brought by foreign students;
• achieving a stronger awareness of the European dimension of education;
• promoting a more critical comparison between our school and the schools of other European countries.
The selection of the 15 people of the staff (14 teachers and 1 employee from the administrative department) participating in the project "Majorana on the M.O.V.E."  takes into account the following criteria:
• the knowledge of the language in order to take full advantage of the benefits deriving from training activities and interactions in host schools abroad, with priority for people attending language courses at schools or universities and/or with language certificates;
• involvement in CLIL methodology, in the use of new methodologies aiming at the inclusion of diversity, with priority for people attending new teaching methodology courses;
• awareness of such issues as inclusion and hospitality of migrants and refugees;
• motivation and awareness of duties connected with the promotion of materials to disseminate the results.
• priority will be granted to the applicants with special needs (disabilities, economical or personal problems).
Participating teachers will take part in the evaluation of the Project through self-monitoring and self-evaluation, before, during and after the activities. They will set personal aims and expectations, they will write a log to update colleagues and students about their experiences abroad and they will write a final report.
The learning experience in a EU dimension and the new tools learnt in the international project will strengthen the teaching competencies of our teachers and will enable them to create an inclusive learning environment well suited for several learning styles and disabilities, including:
• pupils with diverse needs of personalised learning approaches;
• students from different cultural and social backgrounds (i.e. immigrants and refugees).
The impact of the results on the organization will be supported by an effective plan of dissemination through the cooperation between all the parts involved (host school, training provider, participants, students, families).
The dissemination of the project’s results will be carried out using a variety of tools (web site, newsletter, informative corners inside the school, multimedia products as well as communication with other relevant organizations involved in the teaching and training process).
The competencies and knowledge acquired will motivate the teachers of our school to organize
more mobility projects in the future with other schools, both incoming and outgoing.
